    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper applies standard black-hole physics tools to a specific theoretical modification of gravity called \"nonlocal gravity,\" asking how this modification would alter the quasi-periodic oscillation (QPO) signals observed in X-ray light from matter spiraling into black holes. The review board found the methodology internally consistent and the paper competently executed, but assessed it as a routine template calculation applied to one more theory variant without new physical insight or comparison to actual observational data. The most important caveat is that the analysis assumes a non-spinning black hole, while real astrophysical QPO sources host rapidly spinning black holes \u2014 a mismatch that substantially limits the physical applicability of the derived constraints.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper derives the geodesic and epicyclic frequency structure for the Nicolini-type static nonlocal gravity (NLG) black hole (parameter range \u03b1/M \u2264 0.452 per the raw HTML), demonstrates \u03bd_K = \u03bd_\u03b8 from spherical symmetry (reducing 11 QPO models to 7 effective models), and imposes the empirical 3:2 resonance condition to find the upper QPO frequency increasing with \u03b1, a TOV-limited upper frequency of roughly 1450 Hz, and a rough mass bound of order 43.6 M\u2299. The methodology is standard for this class of phenomenological papers; the non-rotating approximation and absence of source-specific data fitting substantially limit the physical applicability of the derived constraints. A discrepancy between reviewer-recovered numerical values (gemini: ~30.6 M\u2299 vs. codex cycle 2: ~43.6 M\u2299) requires PDF verification."
    }
